{"id": "duc04-testb-32:2#7", "contents": "The Justice Department will counter Microsoft's arguments by emphasizing that the sole purpose of antitrust law is to protect consumers. The government will argue that it makes no sense to bless practices that provide short-term benefits but ultimately drive prices up by stifling competition. The Justice Department will ask the court to at least insist that monopolists use the least exclusionary means possible to achieve whatever services they provide customers. Experts agree that the courts will subject Microsoft's restrictive contracts with Internet companies to a balancing test, which would weigh the immediate benefits to consumers against the harm over time of diminished competition in the markets for browsers and operating systems."}
